Patch Set 2:

Connections that are only bound, from vcl perspective, show up as STATE_LISTENING in vpp. Those always need the right ip:port to be set. Connected udp sessions (vcl called connect with proto udp), are either in STATE_OPENED or STATE_READY, the latter if they've been migrated to the right worker. These are by construction constrained to only one destination ip:port pair. Is this the issue you've hit?

Patch Set 2:

> Patch Set 2:
> 
> Connections that are only bound, from vcl perspective, show up as STATE_LISTENING in vpp. Those always need the right ip:port to be set. Connected udp sessions (vcl called connect with proto udp), are either in STATE_OPENED or STATE_READY, the latter if they've been migrated to the right worker. These are by construction constrained to only one destination ip:port pair. Is this the issue you've hit?

What about non-connected udp sessions (app called sendto everytime)? I noticed that in this case VCL will still call connect. But if my app want to send dgram to multi ip:port with same fd, how should i achieve this?

Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)

> Patch Set 2:
> 
> > Patch Set 2:
> > 
> > Connections that are only bound, from vcl perspective, show up as STATE_LISTENING in vpp. Those always need the right ip:port to be set. Connected udp sessions (vcl called connect with proto udp), are either in STATE_OPENED or STATE_READY, the latter if they've been migrated to the right worker. These are by construction constrained to only one destination ip:port pair. Is this the issue you've hit?
> 
> What about non-connected udp sessions (app called sendto everytime)? I noticed that in this case VCL will still call connect. But if my app want to send dgram to multi ip:port with same fd, how should i achieve this?

Fair point, we don't support STATE_OPENED properly today. Could you try with the comment inline to see if it solves the issue?

Patch Set 1:

Not sure I understand why this would be needed. If the event was previously set, we should've generated an EPOLLIN/OUT already, or should generate one once epoll_wait is called. With the change, we'll only have 2 pending event notifications, unless wrk uses epoll in an unexpected way. 

Speaking about this, is wrk using level or edge triggered events? If level-triggered, are you testing with the latest code?

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> Not sure I understand why this would be needed. If the event was previously set, we should've generated an EPOLLIN/OUT already, or should generate one once epoll_wait is called. With the change, we'll only have 2 pending event notifications, unless wrk uses epoll in an unexpected way. 
> 
> Speaking about this, is wrk using level or edge triggered events? If level-triggered, are you testing with the latest code?

Oh, I see, wrk use level-triggered, and my code is 2106 (not support level-triggered). So this commit is a mistake.

Then I checkout the latest code, and test it. Unfortunately, it still doesn't work. It seems that epoll_wait returned duplicate EPOLLIN (1st is generated by vcl_epoll_wait_handle_mq_event(), 2nd is by vcl_epoll_wait_handle_lt()). When wrk responds to the second one, it call read() and returns an error.

Should we do some extra work at vcl_epoll_wait_handle_lt() ? For example, merge the events on same fd ?

When wrk responds to the second one, it call read() and returns an error.
> 
> Should we do some extra work at vcl_epoll_wait_handle_lt() ? For example, merge the events on same fd ?

Yup, we need to avoid generating duplicate events. In theory we should be filtering them out but I suspect this is a case of rx event, followed by complete fifo read, new event, and when epoll wait is called again, the session has new event and is also part of the lt linked list. 

Does this [1] solve the issue? Otherwise we need something smarter :-(

This looks reasonable. That is, although it leads to the crash, the issue seems to be some other piece of code that corrupts/adds a non-vector to nm->recycled_event_data_vectors. Are you by chance using dhcp or some other plugin/extension that calls vlib_process_put_event_data?

Patch Set 3:

> > 
> > I was connecting two vpps through memif intf, and then quit the vpp as the master side, this operation causing the memif linkstatus to be interrupted, and then the status changed to down, then the interface up/down caused this issue. and vlib_process_put_event_data is indeed called in plugins,But I used the following methods：
> > for example:
> > static void
> > dhcp_process_signal_event_safe_i (dhcp_process_req_t *req)
> > {
> >   vlib_main_t *vm = vlib_get_main ();
> > 
> >   ASSERT (vlib_get_thread_index () == 0);
> >   vlib_process_signal_event ();
> > }
> > 
> > static void
> > dhcp_process_signal_event_safe (dhcp_process_req_t *req)
> > {
> >   if (vlib_get_thread_index () != 0)
> >     vl_api_rpc_call_main_thread (dhcp_process_signal_event_safe_i, (u8 *) req,
> > 				 sizeof (*req));
> >   else
> >     dhcp_process_signal_event_safe_i (req);
> > }

> Could you add "_vec_len (event_data) = 0" in vlib_process_put_event_data before the vec_add1 and see if something else forces a crash? I'm guessing that either something frees event_data before calling vlib_process_put_event_data or the data is some stack local.
> 
> It could also be that recycled_event_data_vectors is reallocated/moves if apis are not called from the right threads. Let's see.

Patch Set 2:

This is a known performance issue, unfortunately. The problem are the retransmits after fin is sent. For instance, retransmits that include the last byte in tx fifo should have the fin flag set. In fact, if fin is pending, even the first time we send the last byte we should set the fin flag.

The code today optimizes for "fast path" performance as it tries to avoid constantly checking if it's in a closing state that needs a fin flag by just sending the fin after all data was delivered. Maybe this could be revisited, but the change is in a critical area so it will need a lot of testing. 

I have an old patch that tried to solve this, might try to resurrect it.

Patch Set 2:

Hi Steven,

Shouldn't we do a dedicated 'rename_interface' api & cli ?
I'm under the impression that a lot of interfaces types could benefit
from this, without having to patch all the api calls.

What do you think ?

Cheers
-Nathan

Patch Set 2:

> Patch Set 2:
> 
> Hi Steven,
> 
> Shouldn't we do a dedicated 'rename_interface' api & cli ?
> I'm under the impression that a lot of interfaces types could benefit
> from this, without having to patch all the api calls.
> 
> What do you think ?
> 
> Cheers
> -Nathan

Yes, I was thinking about adding a generic interface CLI
     set interface name <old-name> <new-name>
Implementation will be similar to "set interface rx-mode <intf> <mode>"
It requires each driver to add code to support it with a callback in VNET_DEVICE_CLASS. If there is no callback, we reject the CLI/API because the driver does not have code to support it yet. Each driver can add the callback to support the CLI/API when it is ready. Or is there better way to handle this?

There are differences (e.g. Robot plugin is disabled on production but not on sandbox), but I believe only the 3 environment variables matter for this change.
When testing on Sandbox, I either explicitly set the variables to nexus-enabled values, or unset them to get nexus-disabled behavior. Regardless on actual sandbox configuration.

If 33387 were usable, we would have Nexus disabled and S3 links working, on both Jenkins instances.
Only after the revert I realized we want to temporarily support both types, for purposes of debugging on Sandbox.

Patch Set 1:

thanks for the details! I managed to reproduce the issue: it turns out the 'xsk' object managed by libbpf keep pointers to rx and tx objects. If we re-allocate the rx and/or tx vectors when we grow them, those pointers are staled...
I pushed what I think is the proper fix here: https://gerrit.fd.io/r/c/vpp/+/33595
The main difference with yours is that if the user request 'max' rxq we use the magic value 'rxq_num = 65535' which in your patch would create 65535 elements in all vectors, wasting quite a bit of memory.
Can you try my fix and report the result?
Anyway, thanks again for spotting this!

ok I will try this. Yes, queue num is another question confuse me while i found txq_num is large than rxq_num in my situation, and the last one is allways failed to create.

Patch Set 1:

> Yes, queue num is another question confuse me while i found txq_num is large than rxq_num in my situation, and the last one is allways failed to create.

So the logic is the following: we try to create 1 txq per VPP thread (main + workers) so that any VPP thread can send packets without locking, but if we can't it is not a hard error, we just have to share the txqs between multiple threads with a lock.
If we cannot create the number of rxqs requested by the user on the other hand, it is a hard error.
So if you have say 4 workers and request 4 rxqs, we'll try to create 4 rxqs and 5 txqs (1 main thread + 4 workers). If the underlying interface supports a maximum of 4 queues, we'll create all the requested rxqs but the last txq creation will fail and we'll fallback to shared txqs with locks.

Patch Set 3:

To be clear, in v21.05, -Dplatform=generic only works with arm builds (creates a generic build - not optimized for any platform, usable on all platforms). It's ignored in x86 builds, which uses native build by default (optimized a bit for the platform we're building on. On x86, only the instruction set is optimized this way).

In v21.08, -Dplatform=generic works with everything, so the behavior is different (generic instead of native on x86). We could use machine=default until VPP switches to 21.08 which build generic build for both x86 and arm.

Patch Set 3:

This code does not dump IPv6 table (repeating IPv4 table instead) for some reason.
For max scale, VPP stops responding to PAPI (without crashing) within seven minutes of dumping.

For IPv4 small scale, there are differences in two fields between PAPI, old VAT function and new VAT exec.
One such field is "src" identifying origin of the route, where VAT exec is ID 9 (CLI), and PAPI nad old VAT is ID 8 (API).
Second field is "preference". Old VAT and new VAT exec have default value 0, PAPI has value 1 as added here [0].
Currently, we have no test mixing sources of preferences, so the forwarding behavior is always the same, and I do not expect performance impact either.

[0] https://gerrit.fd.io/r/c/csit/+/20278/27/resources/libraries/python/IPUtil.py#485

Abandoned

Unusable for IPv6 nor big scale tests.
